findings and write the review report.\n\nLet me summarize the issues I\'ve found
:\n\n**Blocking issues:**\n1. Missing `docs/api-contracts/matching-events.yaml` 
- Per `api.md` line 91-96 and "不变量 A", real-time events must have a YAML cont
ract. The PR implements `match:created` Socket.io event but doesn\'t define the 
contract in `matching-events.yaml`.\n\n2. API response field naming inconsistenc
y - `SwipeActionResponse` uses camelCase (`isMatch`, `matchId`, `conversationId`
) while the project convention per `api.md` URL规范 is snake_case for all JSON f
ields. This is also inconsistent with other DTOs in the same module (`Recommenda
tionResponseDto`, `MatchListResponseDto` both use snake_case).\n\n**Major issues
:**\n1. `MatchingService.queryCandidatesFromDb` excludes users who passed on the
current user (`SELECT actor_id FROM match_actions WHERE target_id = ? AND action
= \'pass\'`). This deviates from the exec plan (`TASK-matching.md` line 98-99) w
hich only excludes current user\'s own actions. It also creates a privacy leak (
users can infer they were passed on) and overly restricts the candidate pool.\n\
n2. `MatchListItem` hardcodes `identifier: \'match_list_item\'` for all list ite
ms. Per `flutter.md` accessibility guidelines, identifiers should be unique for 
Maestro E2E testing. In a list, this means Maestro can only ever tap the first i
tem.\n\n3. `MatchListPage` doesn\'t navigate to profile setup on `ProfileIncompl
eteException`. It shows an error message but doesn\'t redirect, unlike `HomePage
` which navigates to `/profile-setup`. This creates inconsistent UX.\n\n4. `Matc
hingSocketClient` doesn\'t handle token refresh or reconnection. If the socket d
isconnects (e.g., network change, token expiry), the user won\'t receive match n
otifications until app restart.\n\n5. `HomePage._initSocket` reads the access to
ken from `SecureStorage` instead of using the already-available token from `Auth
Bloc` state. This is redundant and could fail independently.\n\n**Minor issues:*
*\n1. `MatchingBloc._onSwipeActionSubmitted` removes the card from UI before the
API call succeeds. If the API fails, the card is gone and can\'t be re-swipe.\n\
n2. `MatchingService.getRecommendations` returns empty array when lock acquisiti
on fails and cache is still empty, rather than waiting longer or querying DB wit
hout lock.\n\n3. `MatchingGateway.handleConnection` doesn\'t check profile compl
etion. While REST APIs are guarded, incomplete users can still connect to the ma
tching namespace socket.\n\n4. BDD test for "Profile incomplete blocks recommend
ations" has a weak assertion that accepts code 0 (which happens when guard is mo
cked). This reduces test value.\n\n5. The `SwipeActionResponse` contract in `mat
ching.yaml` uses camelCase, same as the implementation, but inconsistent with pr
oject convention.\n\nWait, I should re-evaluate whether the missing `matching-ev
ents.yaml` is truly blocking. Let me re-read the spec:\n\nFrom `api.md`:\n> **不
变量 A**：后端每新增一个 `server.emit()` / `socket.emit()` 事件，必须同时满足：\
n> - [ ] `docs/api-contracts/<module>-events.yaml` 中定义了该事件的 Schema\n> - 
[ ] `apps/mobile/lib/core/network/socket_client.dart` 中注册了对应的事件监听器\n
> - [ ] 至少一个 Mobile BLoC / Service 中消费了该事件并改变了 UI 状态\n> - [ ] B
DD 测试中有步骤验证该事件被正确接收\n\nThe PR satisfies items 2-4 but NOT item 1
. This is explicitly called out as a "强制不变量" (mandatory invariant). So yes,
this is a blocking issue.\n\nFor the camelCase vs snake_case issue in `SwipeActi
onResponse`: The `api.md` says "资源命名：snake_case" under URL规范, but for res
ponse fields, the `common.yaml` and other DTOs use snake_case consistently. The 
`matching.yaml` contract itself uses snake_case for `RecommendationCard` and `Ma
tchListItem`. The only exception is `SwipeActionResponse`. This is a clear conve
ntion violation. But is it blocking? It means the generated models use camelCase
, and the manual `SwipeResult` model also uses camelCase. So the mobile code is 
consistent with the API response. But it\'s inconsistent with the rest of the AP
I. I\'d mark this as Major rather than Blocking, because the system works - it\'
s just a convention violation.\n\nWait, actually, let me re-check the API respon
se format. The controller returns the service result directly:\n```typescript\nr
eturn {\n  code: 0,\n  message: "success",\n  data: result,\n};\n```\n\nAnd `res
ult` is `{ isMatch: boolean; matchId?: string; conversationId?: string }`.\n\nBu
t the OpenAPI contract defines `SwipeActionResponse` with camelCase. So the gene
rated Dart model expects camelCase. And the mobile `SwipeResult` model also expe
cts camelCase. So the entire chain is consistent, just inconsistent with the res
t of the project.\n\nThis is a **Major** issue because it violates project conve
ntions and could cause confusion for future API consumers.\n\nLet me also check:
is there any issue with the `MatchingGateway` not having `@UseGuards`? In NestJS
WebSocket gateways, guards can be applied but they work differently. The `handle
Connection` method is the right place to validate. The gateway correctly validat
es JWT but doesn\'t check profile completion. This is a gap but not blocking sin
ce incomplete users can\'t trigger matches through REST APIs.\n\nActually, I sho
uld also check: does the `MatchingBloc` test file use `bloc_test` package? Looki
ng at the pubspec.yaml, `bloc_test` is not in dev_dependencies. The tests use `m
ocktail` and `flutter_test` directly with `expectLater` and `emitsInOrder`. This
is fine.\n\nLet me check if the `SwipeCardStack` background cards use `Positione
d` correctly. Looking at the code:\n```dart\nif (cards.length > 2)\n  Positioned
(\n    top: 8,\n    left: 0,\n    right: 0,\n    child: _buildBackgroundCard(car
ds[2], scale: 0.9),\n  ),\n```\n\nThis uses `Positioned` with `left: 0, right: 0
` but no explicit `width`. The child is a `Transform.scale` wrapping a `SwipeCar
d`. The `SwipeCard` doesn\'t have an explicit width either - it uses `margin` an
d `AspectRatio`. In a `Stack` with `Positioned(left: 0, right: 0)`, the width is
determined by the parent constraints. This should be OK because the `Stack` is i
nside a `GestureDetector` which is inside an `Expanded` in `HomePage`. So the `S
tack` has constrained width.\n\nOne more thing: the `SwipeCard` uses `AspectRati
o(aspectRatio: 0.75)` but it\'s inside a `Stack` in `SwipeCardStack`. The `Stack
` doesn\'t constrain the height, but the `HomePage` puts the `GestureDetector` i
nside an `Expanded`, so the card stack fills the available height. The `AspectRa
tio` widget will try to maintain its aspect ratio within the given constraints. 
This should be fine.\n\nNow let me think about the `EmptyRecommendationView` tex
t: "附近暂无可推荐用户" - this matches the PRD\'s empty state message "附近暂无
可推荐用户". Good.\n\nThe `MatchListPage` empty state says "还没有匹配成功的好友
" and "继续滑动，发现感兴趣的人吧". This is not explicitly defined in the PRD bu
t it\'s reasonable.\n\nLet me check one more potential issue: the `MatchingServi
ce.getRecommendations` caches candidate IDs with scores, but `buildRecommendatio
ns` fetches profiles from DB and recalculates distances. It doesn\'t use the cac
hed scores for ordering! Let me re-read:\n\n```typescript\nprivate async buildRe
commendations(\n  userIds: string[],\n  currentUserId: string,\n): Promise<Recom
mendationResponseDto[]> {\n  // ...\n  const profiles = await this.profileRepo.f
indBy({ user_id: In(userIds) });\n  const profileMap = new Map(profiles.map((p) 
=> [p.user_id, p]));\n\n  return userIds\n    .map((id) => {\n      const p = pr
ofileMap.get(id);\n      if (!p) return null;\n      // ...\n      return rec;\n
   })\n    .filter((r): r is RecommendationResponseDto => r !== null);\n}\n```\n
\nIt iterates over `userIds` (which is in the original cached order) and maps th
em. Since `userIds` comes from the cache in the original score-sorted order, the
returned array preserves that order. But `profileRepo.findBy({ user_id: In(userI
ds) })` doesn\'t guarantee order! The database might return profiles in a differ
ent order than `userIds`. But since we build a `profileMap` and then iterate ove
r `userIds` in order, the final result IS in the correct order. So this is fine.
\n\nWait, but what about the distance calculation in `buildRecommendations`? It 
recalculates distance using the `haversine` function, while the cache was built 
using the DB Haversine calculation. These should be consistent (same formula, sa
me Earth radius). The DB uses `6371` and the code also uses `6371`. Good.\n\nNow
let me check the `matching.service.spec.ts` for the `getRecommendations` test wi
th cache hit. It tests that `profileRepo.findBy` returns profiles and the result
has the right user_id. Good.\n\nLet me also check the `MatchingService.getMatchL
ist` method. It uses `qb.take(limit + 1)` to check if there\'s a next page. This
is the standard cursor pagination pattern. It then slices off the extra item. Go
od.\n\nBut wait, `getMatchList` doesn\'t filter out unmatched/blocked users from
the match list. The PRD says "列表中的用户若被拉黑，则自动过滤（unmatched 状态）
". The current implementation queries `status = \'matched\'` but doesn\'t check 
`blocks`. This is a **Major** issue because the PRD explicitly requires filterin
g blocked users from the match list.\n\nActually, looking at the PRD `v1-matchin
g.md` line 196:\n> 列表中的用户若被拉黑，则自动过滤（`unmatched` 状态）。\n\nThi
s says if a user is blocked, the match status should be `unmatched`, and the mat
ching side reads with `status = \'matched\'` filter. So if the block module upda
tes the match status to `unmatched`, the matching list will naturally filter it 
